The Destruction of the Tower of the Fomoiri by Nemed's People


3. TOIRINNIS muighe ceitne
4. fris an raittear toraigh thuaisgeirt eirenn
4. aniu .i. caithir conuing mic faobhuir
6. {i}s innte ro diothuighedh fomhoraigh
7. le clannuibh neimheadh . Tri toisigh
8. ro badur gan toghuil sin thuir conuing
9. .i. fearghus leathdearg mac neimheadh et beo
10. thach mac iarmhuineil mic neimeadh agus semon
11. mac sdairn mic neimheadh Roinnsead eire
12. an ttrir eatarra trian beothaigh ó
13. toirinnis go boinn trian semoin
14. go bealach chonghlais Trian fearghusa
15. leithdheirg ó bealach chonglais go toraigh
16. ttuaisgeirt eireann

Notes

1. Confusingly, "dia" could mean either "for his [brother]" or "from his [brother]". While one might expect Partholon to be attempting to disrupt his brother's succession in his own favour, the fact that the passage goes on to state that his brother assumed the kingship with no apparent conflict with Parthalon suggests that Parthalon was acting on his brother's behalf.
